1 0 0 1 56 732.0 Tm (Naming the Spectrum: The Emergence of Basic Colour Terms in Twelve Unrelated Languages) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 718.0 Tm () Tj
/F1 9 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 704.0 Tm (Priya Raghunathan) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 690.0 Tm (Studies in Comparative Linguistics, Vol. 18, No. 2 \(1991\) - JID-008) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 676.0 Tm () Tj
/F2 12 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 658.0 Tm (Abstract) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 644.0 Tm (Languages differ in how many basic colour terms they encode and where they draw the) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 630.0 Tm (boundaries between them. Surveying twelve unrelated languages with a standardised) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 616.0 Tm (colour-naming task, this paper finds broad support for a constrained order in which colour) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 602.0 Tm (vocabularies expand, while documenting systematic exceptions at the blue-green boundary that) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 588.0 Tm (resist the standard sequence. I argue that the order reflects perceptual salience filtered) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 574.0 Tm (through cultural priorities rather than perception alone.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 560.0 Tm () Tj
/F2 12 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 542.0 Tm (Introduction) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 528.0 Tm (Why do some languages have a single word covering both blue and green while others split the) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 514.0 Tm (spectrum into a dozen named regions? The question sits at the intersection of perception,) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 500.0 Tm (which is broadly shared across humanity, and language, which is endlessly various. The) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 486.0 Tm (colour lexicon is a rare domain where the two can be measured against each other directly.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 472.0 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 56 458.0 Tm (This study administered an identical colour-naming task to speakers of twelve languages) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 444.0 Tm (chosen for their lack of close relation, in order to test how far a single ordering of) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 430.0 Tm (colour-term acquisition holds across genuinely independent cases.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 416.0 Tm () Tj
/F2 12 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 398.0 Tm (Method) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 384.0 Tm (Each participant was shown a standardised array of colour chips spanning hue, saturation,) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 370.0 Tm (and lightness, and asked to name each chip with a single everyday word. A term counted as) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 356.0 Tm ('basic' only if it was monolexemic, widely agreed upon, and not subsumed under another term.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 342.0 Tm (This screening is essential, because every language has many more colour words than basic) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 328.0 Tm (terms.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 314.0 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 56 300.0 Tm (We then mapped the region of the array that each basic term covered, producing for every) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 286.0 Tm (language a partition of colour space. Comparing these partitions across the twelve languages) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 272.0 Tm (is the heart of the analysis.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 258.0 Tm () Tj
/F2 12 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 240.0 Tm (A Constrained Order) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 226.0 Tm (The languages fell, with notable regularity, along a single ladder of elaboration. Those) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 212.0 Tm (with the fewest terms divided colour space into broad warm and cool, or light and dark,) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 198.0 Tm (categories. As the inventory grew, terms for red, then for yellow and green, then for blue,) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 184.0 Tm (appeared in a largely fixed succession.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 170.0 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 56 156.0 Tm (This ordering is unlikely to be coincidental across unrelated languages, and it points to a) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 142.0 Tm (perceptual scaffolding shared by all speakers. The most salient distinctions of human vision) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 128.0 Tm (appear to be named first, with finer distinctions added as a vocabulary matures.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 114.0 Tm () Tj
/F2 12 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 96.0 Tm (The Blue-Green Exceptions) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 82.0 Tm (The clean order broke down at the boundary between blue and green. Several languages) Tj
