/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 736.0 Tm (maintained a single term spanning both long after the standard sequence predicts they should) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 722.0 Tm (have split, and the split, when it came, did not always fall where perception would suggest.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 708.0 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 56 694.0 Tm (These exceptions correlate with the cultural prominence of particular materials, dyes, and) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 680.0 Tm (natural features rather than with any perceptual threshold. I argue they show that the) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 666.0 Tm (acquisition order is not dictated by perception alone. Perception sets the menu, but culture) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 652.0 Tm (chooses the order of courses, and at the blue-green boundary that choice is visibly) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 638.0 Tm (contingent. The languages that delayed the split longest were, without exception, those) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 624.0 Tm (whose speakers had the least daily need to distinguish the sky from the foliage, a pattern) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 610.0 Tm (that ties naming order to lived priority rather than to any property of the eye.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 596.0 Tm () Tj
/F2 12 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 578.0 Tm (Conclusion) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 564.0 Tm (Across twelve unrelated languages, basic colour terms expand in a broadly constrained order) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 550.0 Tm (that betrays a shared perceptual foundation, yet the persistent blue-green exceptions show) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 536.0 Tm (culture asserting itself against that foundation. The colour lexicon is best read as) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 522.0 Tm (perception and culture in negotiation, neither wholly free nor wholly fixed.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 508.0 Tm () Tj
